    "error": {
        "code": "BadRequest",
        "message": "Shared disk '[Disk]' with maxShares 3 supports only Disk CachingType 'None'."
    }

'2022-04-22T20:14:50Z', 'closed_at': None, 'author_association': 'NONE', 'active_lock_reason': None, 'body': "My question stems from the below MS page on Azure Virtual Machine and Disk Performance.

https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/azure/virtual-machines/disks-performance

I understand the VM and the disk have separate IOPs/throughput limits and the performance will be capped at the lower of the two, so that is not the question.

While describing how reads and writes work with caching, the below two paragraphs clearly say a read will be counted against both the cached and uncached limits of the VM.

“When a read is performed and the desired data is not available on the cache, the read request is relayed to the disk. Then the disk surfaces it to both the cache and the VM. This read is counted toward both the VM's uncached limit and the VM's cached limit.”

and

“When a write is performed, the write has to be written to both the cache and the disk before it is considered complete. This write is counted toward the VM's uncached limit and the VM's cached limit.”

They then go on to say by enabling caching on some disks and not on other disks you can get a total IOPS of the uncached plus the cached limits. “This configuration allows your virtual machines to get a total storage IO of the cached limit plus the uncached limit.”

My question is, how is it possible to get a total storage IO of the cached limit plus the uncached limit when many of the reads and all of the writes to disks with caching will count against both the cached and uncached limits. Am I missing something here?

---

'2022-02-15T18:41:21Z', 'closed_at': None, 'author_association': 'NONE', 'active_lock_reason': None, 'body': '
Since client machine domain join is not a must for either AD DS scenarios I think an additional validation can be included on this Debug script that it checks if the client machine has line of sight to the Domain through the command just the script should ask for the domain FQDN

nltest /dsgetdc:<domainfqdn>

Other frequent issue is when storage key credentials are cached on the client machine that users have the wrong impression they can successfully access the File Share with domain credentials, so include an additional validation for this can be useful to avoid those kind of issues.

Regards,
  
---
